<a href="javascript:card_browser(19)">Bred for Battle</a>    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <b>***PLEASE READ STRATEGY BEFORE REVIEWING***</b><br />
<br />
<b>***STRATEGY EDIT***</b><br />
<br />
Free Peoples Out:<br />
Glamdring<br />
Wizard&#39;s Staff<br />
<br />
Free Peoples In:<br />
Shadowfax<br />
Aragorn&#39;s Bow<br />
<br />
Shadow Out:<br />
Ferocity<br />
Bred for Battle<br />
Grima<br />
Greed<br />
<br />
Shadow In:<br />
Uruk Regular x3<br />
Saruman, KoI<br />
<br />
<i>Why the changes?</i><br />
Well, I listened to your criticisms (I know some of you might think that I don&#39;t by my constant sarcasm) and I tested them.  While all of you are right on some level, some suggestions didn&#39;t fit for this deck (or at least the way I&#39;m playing it).  But those that were right, absolutely, are reflected in these changes.  I have grown paranoid over my own Moria engine, so I erred on the side of Moria protection.  But I have Sting.  Shadowfax is better for it&#39;s versatility.  The Wizard&#39;s Staff vitality isn&#39;t necessary...but is expensive.  So, I&#39;m pulling that.  Meanwhile, having the extra archery is more versatile, because it affects every culture.  The pumps and Greed are nice, but they certainly aren&#39;t necessary and Grima simply pales in comparison to the Uruk Swarm (which I only recently tested), so change to the swarm engine and kill some ring-bearers.  As for those of you who suggested that I need Servants, it doesn&#39;t fit my playstyle with Trust.  I emphasize surviving skirmishes not winning them.<br />
<br />
Oh, I should have known better than to make global generalizations about the meta.  I tried to make it clear that I wasn&#39;t saying any strategies were dead, but I did use some pretty strong words against twilight choke.  No, it is certainly not dead, but I do see it much less than before.  Of course, that&#39;s the funny thing about metas...they&#39;re different from place to place.<br />
<br />
<b>***END STRATEGY EDIT***</b><br />
<br />
Old strategies are often the best strategies!  I believe that this is true now more than ever!  This deck, as you might infer from the title, is about Gandalf and Saruman doing what they do best--make those around them stronger.  This deck employs a solid fellowship and solid shadow to take whatever you come up with . . . and overcome it.<br />
<br />
<b>Changes in the meta:</b><br />
<br />
<b>Elven Allies Stay Home--</b>It used to be guaranteed that, in at least one game per tournament, either you or your opponent would set up the Lorien ally engine because it killed minions and guaranteed the double to 6; but since the Lorien allies don’t have a summer home in Rohan, they can’t grant the fellowship safe-haven.  Thus, people have (for the most part) abandoned the strategy.  Moreover, with the wane of the Elven ally archetype, we also find Directed Archery receding.  Now, this is not to say that these strategies aren’t viable, but rather that people are focusing on new fellowships, which means two things: 1) Archery is less of a threat; 2) A fellowship that can guarantee a double move and a shadow that denies them will win games.<br />
<br />
<b>Easterlings Teach the Heimlich--</b>Cards such as Ithilien Wilderness and Wizard’s Vale have made it impractical to take twilight denial fellowships to tournaments.  Again, this is not to say that they are dead, only that they are not prevalent.  The result is that the emphasis has shifted from ‘getting the best cards for the fewest twilight’ to ‘getting the most out of the twilight you’re given’.  True, both of these philosophies translate to twilight efficiency, but it IS a slight change in strategy.  It’s more important to build a bend-but-don’t-break fellowship and it’s acceptable to adopt previously overlooked powerful-but-expensive shadow strategies.<br />
<br />
<b>The Rise of the Era of Men--</b>Many players are exploring Ringbounds, Raiders, Rohan, and Dunland.  It’s what’s new and people like to explore new frontiers!  This is important because it means that orcs, though more powerful than ever (though many would disagree), are falling by the wayside.  This is a very dangerous secret because it means that you have to prepare more than ever while sparing fewer cards in defense.  Meanwhile, of the four cultures of Men described above, each has drastically different strategies . . . but each (with Raiders being a possible exception) relies on winning skirmishes.<br />
<br />
<b>A Very Good Place to Start--</b>In Fellowship block, it was a fairly safe assumption that your games would begin with an Inn at the head of the path.  In the Tower meta, there are 5 strong starting sites.  You can no longer assume that your opponent will play a starting site that benefits you (though most will continue to pull Aragorn).  Of equal importance is the fact that there is no site that pulls Sam.  With Raiders being better than Sauron at adding burdens (orcs not “the enemy”), we find that more people are bidding conservative, and having a means to remove burdens is more important than ever.<br />
<br />
So, what truths do we glean from this?  Well, other than what I have already stated, we learn: 1) Because of larger twilight pools, increased early options, and companion codependence, Large fellowships are the order of the day; 2) Twilight management (but not twilight choke) is important; 3) Fellowships that win skirmishes, take wounds without dying, and double move just once (twice is ideal) will win their games; 4) Most importantly, you must have options.<br />
<br />
Speaking of options, let’s look at them . . . <br />
<br />
<b>Nertea and Enquea:</b>  Big fellowship defense!  Nertea and Enquea, in my honest opinion, are the two most versatile minions in the game.  They are the reason we play OEG.  Nertea is the reason I don’t play more of many useful minions, and he is the reason I love (and fear) the Cavern Entrance.<br />
<br />
<b>Saruman’s Power and Grown Suddenly Tall:</b>  Yes, I realize that my conditions win games.  Yes, these two cards kill my important conditions.  Still, it has been my experience that, at times, an opponent’s conditions hurt me more than mine help.  In those situations, I would gladly sacrifice all my conditions to get rid of theirs.  If that is not the case, don’t play the card.<br />
<br />
<b>Sites 1, 2, 5, 7, and 9:</b> Many players don’t play Gimli.  My site 1 denies the Riddermark and allows me to pull a support companion.  Site 2 provides incentive for my opponent to stop should he win the bid and make me go second.  Furthermore, should I stop, it can substitute for a sanctuary, allowing me to double to 4.  That, in most cases, will be enough for me to catch up.  I usually have Saruman available without help from the site.  Therefore, having a means of effectively playing Uruk-hai to key off of him is what’s most important.  As for 7, both my fellowship and shadow rely on skirmish abilities, so I cannot emphasize enough how important it is to avoid the Cavern Entrance.  Finally, your site 9 is your coup de grace.  Assuming, your opponent has stayed in the lead and gotten to site 9, you have probably killed off companions.  And since you have targeted Filibert with your Assassin, Saruman and 3 Uruk-hai will probably be enough to finish the job.<br />
<br />
<b>Treebeard:</b> Treebeard is my guarantee for a double move.  With him, the move to the Wizard’s Vale (or that Dunland place) is safe.  Also, he allows me to heal almost anybody with my extra copies of Gandalf and Aragorn.<br />
<br />
<b>Eowyn, LoR:</b> Eowyn allows me to play my big fellowship with little fear of losing them to Enquea or Hate or what have you.  Also, she is a repository for many of the more useful items that you get early before a Gondor companion arrives.  Keep her out of skirmishes and heal her whenever possible (though, it really pisses her off to be kept away from the action . . . come on, read the books).<br />
<br />
<b>Glamdring and Sting:</b> Shadowfax and Hobbit Swords appear to be attractive substitutes for the two super-swords.  However, orcs are still a factor for which you must prepare.  And knowing what your opponent has is the best means of twilight management available.<br />
<br />
<b>Legolas and Gimli:</b>  This deck is about winning skirmishes.  Legolas and Gimli help you do that.  So, while it might be tempting to play Greenleaf, Lego’s knives are much more important than his arrows.<br />
<br />
<b>A Wizard is Never Late x2:</b>  Most Gandalf decks include one copy just for a better chance to draw Gandalf early.  I play 2 because of the immense power of Albert and Treebeard.  If I play Moria or Isengard, I need Albert ASAP!  If not, Treebeard is a welcome addition.  (Oh yeah!  Six ways to an early Gandalf ain’t bad, either.)<br />
<br />
<b>O Elbereth! Gilthoniel! and Filibert:</b>  It always amuses me how many players have not yet realized the power of certain cards.  So, for those of you who might not know, let me explain.  Filibert is a must in EVERY fellowship.  He ensures that as long as your ring-bearer has 2 open vitality, your opponent must play more minions than you have companions in order to win.  Otherwise, even if he kills every companion but Frodo, no matter how many minions dog pile him, the ring is safe, because you’ll exert to prevent the skirmish and walk away unscathed. As an addendum, the only way your opponent can typically achieve that many minions against a large fellowship is by using Nertea, and that’s where OEG comes in.  Assign Frodo first to Nertea and discard OEG; then let Filibert protect you.  Game Over!  Frodo survives!  You win!<br />
<br />
<b>Thror’s Map:</b>  This used to be THE most powerful rare in the game.  Decipher realized that and changed its text so that it wouldn’t be quite so dominating.  For some reason, people associated that change with a complete loss of usefulness.  However, when you consider that most decks play 2 hobbits in addition to Frodo (Filibert and Sam) and that you often can surmise your opponent’s path based on what you see, Thror’s Map, despite its diminished power, becomes very attractive.  (Have I mentioned how much I fear the Cavern Entrance?)<br />
<br />
<b>Boromir / Faramir / Sam:</b>  Faramir and Sam trigger Frodo’s text and prevent Easterlings from adding burdens.  SoH effectively removes 4 burdens.  Faramir, SoD is unstoppable when fully equipped.  Boromir, DoMT stays alive forever.<br />
<br />
<b>What I lack:</b>  I don’t have a means to liberate sites, and that is my one concern.  However, when you consider that I can kill conditions and win skirmishes (with or without possessions) reliably, I should have little to fear from site control decks.  Oh sure, they will control sites, but as long as I can keep that to no more than 2 sites, I think my fellowship is strong enough to bare the consequences.<br />
<br />
Well, that’s it for the cards.  Now, let’s look at my suggested game-strategy.<br />
<br />
Bid 2+.  Assuming that your opponent has no way to add burdens, you’ll remove what burdens you bid with Faramir and Sam.  You can bid higher if you choose because Trust wins skirmishes, Sam prevents burden adding, and Narya is an option; however I cite 2 as the magic number because it comes with few consequences, and those burdens will be removed.<br />
<br />
If you win the bid, choose to go first.  Start Eowyn and Legolas and pull Gimli.  Thus, when you pull Gandalf, he’s already powered up.  If your opponent wins the bid, your start depends on their site one.  Select from Eowyn, Gimli, and Legolas as appropriate.<br />
<br />
Set up your fellowship.  If you started Eowyn, don’t be afraid to play your companions, because she can protect them.  If you didn’t, be wary of the large fellowship killers.  Win the skirmishes that are important.  Your shadow will stop your opponent.  For that reason, don’t take any undue risks.  You can catch up in the middle portion just based on site 5 alone if you prepare right.  You will get most of your kills through overwhelms, so use your pumps wisely.  Also, pick your moment to use Nertea.  He wins games.  Use Treebeard to get you to site 8.  He too wins games.<br />
<br />
Anyway, that’s the deck.  Comments, criticisms, and/or questions are always welcome!<br />
<br />
<I>Devon “Old School!” Clark</I><br />
